       <div id="tabs-2">
            <p>Brachytherapy – An internal treatment procedure that involves implanting radioactive sources (isotopes) in or very near the target tumor. Dr. Kramer is skilled in placing brachytherapy treatment “seeds.”</p>
            <p>Cancer – An abnormal malignant growth of cells that invade nearby tissues and often spread to other sites in the body, interfering with the normal function of the affected sites.</p>
            <p>Chemotherapy – Treatment of disease by chemical agents. Anticancer drugs generally inhibit the proliferation of cells. Medical oncologists such as Dr. Fang prescribe chemotherapy, cell regulating therapy, immunotherapy, and hormonal therapy when warranted.</p>
            <p>CT Scanner – Sort of a circular x-ray machine, the scanner’s images are reconstructed in a computer that provides a visualization of tissue, bones and tumors. The scans are used to not only detect tumors, but also to help plan and carry out treatment. There is a dedicated CT Scanner on site at the Sky Lakes Cancer Treatment Center.</p>
            <p>IMRT -- Intensity Modulated Radiation Therapy. Computers automatically adjust the strength and the shape of the radiation beam along with shielding devices inside the device to deliver radiation more precisely to the tumor while relatively sparing surrounding normal tissues.</p>
            <p>IGRT – Image Guided Radiation Therapy, used with IMRT, provides your physician increased certainty that the radiation is hitting the intended target while missing normal tissues. The Sky Lakes Cancer Treatment Center radiation oncology Department uses both IMRT and IGRT to help patients.</p>
            <p>Metastasis – Spread of a tumor from its site of origin to distant sites, usually through the bloodstream, the lymphatic system, or across a cavity. (Verb, metastasize)</p>
            <p>Radiation Therapy – Also called radiotherapy. Treatment of certain forms of cancer and some benign conditions by radiation produced by special machines called linear accelerators or by radioactive isotopes. The radiation interferes with the division of cells and the synthesis of DNA.</p>
            <p>Tumor – Growth of tissue characterized by uncontrolled cell proliferation. A tumor may be benign or malignant; localized or invasive. Also called neoplasm.</p>
